{"cursor":"5556","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox Minister\n| name = VladimÃ­r Clementis image =Bratislava_Relief_Vladimira_Clementisa.jpg\n| imagesize =120px order =Foreign Minister of Czechoslovakia term_start =1948\n| term_end =1950 deputy = predecessor = Jan Masaryk successor = Viliam Å irokÃ½\n| birth_date = birth_place =Tisovec, Austria-Hungary death_date = death_place =\n| Prague, Czechoslovakia spouse = constituency = party =Czechoslovak Communist\n| Party signature =\n}}\n\n'VladimÃ­r \"Vlado\" Clementis' (September 20, 1902 Tisovec (Tiszolc) - December 3,\n1952 Prague) was a Slovak minister, politician, lawyer, publicist, literary\ncritic, author and a prominent member of the Czechoslovak Communist Party. He\nmarried LÃ­da PÃ¡tkovÃ¡, a daughter of a branch director of Czech Hypothec Bank in\nBratislava, in March 1933. He became a Communist MP in 1935. Before the\nbeginning of the World War II, in 1938, he emigrated to Paris. His criticism of\nthe Molotov-Ribbentrop pact in 1939, contradicted the policies of the\nCzechoslovak Communist Party exiled in Moscow and triggered an intra-party\ninvestigation overseen by Viliam Å irokÃ½ (who came to Paris from Moscow).\n\nAt the outbreak of World War II in September 1939, he was put into prison as a\nknown Communist, and later evacuated to a British concentration camp. After\nrelease, he decided to spend the war in London, where he broadcast speeches on\nthe radio calling for all Slovaks to fight against the Nazis. Returning in 1945,\nhe became Vice-Minister of Foreign Affairs under the first post-war government.\nAs a representative of Czechoslovakia, he signed UN Charter in San Francisco on\n26 June, 1945. After a coup d'Ã©tat, which he helped organise, he succeeded Jan\nMasaryk as Foreign Minister. In 1948, in his new role, he played a decisive role\nin organising Czechoslovakian's part of the Operation Balak by providing a help\nto the newly founded Israeli Air Force. In 1950, he was forced to resign amid\naccused of being a \"deviationist\". He was then arrested and officially charged\nfor an illegal attempt to cross the state boundaries, later changed for a more\nserious crime to be a \"bourgeois nationalist\" and participating in the Trotskyite-Titoite-\nZionist conspiracy. After being convicted in the SlÃ¡nskÃ½ show trial, he was\nhanged, along with Rudolf SlÃ¡nskÃ½, on 3 December 1952. His ashes were scattered\non a road close to Prague. His wife, LÃ­da, received only her husband's two pipes\nand tobacco and was discharged from a prison. [http://spravy.pravda.sk/ako-pykal-siroky-za-smrt-clementisa-db2-\n/sk_domace.asp?c=A080119_130802_sk_domace_p23] Pravda, 19 January 2008. \n\nIn the famous photograph from 21 February, 1948 (the story is described in [[The\nBook of Laughter and Forgetting]] by Milan Kundera), VladimÃ­r Clementis stands\nnext to Klement Gottwald, who later, after a coup d'Ã©tat, became the President\nof Czechoslovakia. When VladimÃ­r Clementis was executed in 1952, he was erased\nfrom the photograph (along with the photographer Karel HÃ¡jek?).  [http://multimedia.ctk.cz/cs/foto/document/1019167/unor-1948-klement-gottwald-\nprojev-staromestske-namesti-manipulace] Photograph of Gottwald and Clementis\nfrom 21 February 1948, Prague, Czechoslovakia, Czech News Agency, Ätk.cz .\n [http://multimedia.ctk.cz/cs/foto/document/1019166/unor-1948-klement-gottwald-\nprojev-staromestske-namesti-retus-manipulace] Retouched photograph of Gottwald\nand Clementis from 21 February 1948, Prague, Czechoslovakia, Czech News Agency,\nÄtk.cz .\n","linknr":198,"url":"Vladimír_Clementis","recorded":1375085175,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Vladim%C3%ADr_Clementis&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Vladim%C3%ADr_Clementis&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wik